# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aws-s3
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aws-s3/amazon-s3] Amazon S3 manages data with an object storage architecture which aims to provide scalability, high availability, and low latency with high durability.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-s3] The basic storage units of Amazon S3 are objects which are organized into buckets.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-s3] Each object is identified by a unique, user-assigned key.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-s3] Buckets can be managed using the console provided by Amazon S3, programmatically with the AWS SDK, or the REST application programming interface.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-s3] Objects can be up to five terabytes in size.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-s3] Requests are authorized using an access control list associated with each object bucket and support versioning which is disabled by default.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-s3] Amazon S3 can be used to replace static web-hosting infrastructure with HTTP client-accessible objects, index document support, and error document support.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-s3] The Amazon AWS authentication mechanism allows the creation of authenticated URLs, valid for a specified amount of time.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-s3] Every item in a bucket can also be served as a BitTorrent feed.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-s3] The Amazon S3 store can act as a seed host for a torrent and any BitTorrent client can retrieve the file.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-s3] This can drastically reduce the bandwidth cost for the download of popular objects.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-s3] A bucket can be configured to save HTTP log information to a sibling bucket; this can be used in data mining operations.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-s3] Various User Mode File System (FUSE)–based file systems for Linux or other Unix-like operating systems can be used to mount an S3 bucket as a file system.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-s3] The semantics of the Amazon S3 file system are not that of a POSIX file system, so the file system may not behave entirely as expected.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-s3] Implementations include Rclone and AWS's own Mountpoint for S3.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-s3] Amazon S3 offers nine different storage classes with different levels of durability, availability, and performance requirements.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-s3] The Amazon S3 Glacier storage classes above are distinct from Amazon Glacier, which is a separate product with its own APIs.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-s3] An object in S3 can be between 0 bytes and 5 TB.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-s3] If an object is larger than 5 TB, it must be divided into chunks prior to uploading.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-s3] When uploading, Amazon S3 allows a maximum of 5 GB in a single upload operation; hence, objects larger than 5 GB must be uploaded via the S3 multipart upload API.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-s3] As of 2025, S3 stores 500 trillion objects, 100s of exabytes of data, serves 200 million requests per second, and peaks at about 1 petabyte per second in bandwidth.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-s3] The broad adoption of Amazon S3 and related tooling has given rise to competing services based on the S3 API.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-s3] These services use the standard programming interface but are differentiated by their underlying technologies and business models.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-s3] A standard interface enables better competition from rival providers and allows economies of scale in implementation, among other benefits.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-s3] Users are not required to go directly to Amazon as several storage providers such as Cloudian, Backblaze B2, Wasabi offer S3-compatible storage with options of on-premises and private cloud deployments.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-s3] Several open-source implementations of S3-compatible object store servers can be self-hosted, such as Garage.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-s3] IBM Cloud Object Storage also offers a cloud-based S3-compatible option of Object Storage.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-s3] Amazon Web Services introduced Amazon S3 in 2006.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-s3] In November 2017, AWS added default encryption capabilities at bucket level.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] Clients often use this in combination with autoscaling (a process that allows a client to use more computing in times of high application usage, and then scale down to reduce costs when there is less traffic).
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] These cloud computing web services provide various services related to networking, compute, storage, middleware, IoT and other processing capacity, as well as software tools via AWS server farms.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] This frees clients from managing, scaling, and patching hardware and operating systems.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] One of the foundational services is Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), which allows users to have at their disposal a virtual cluster of computers, with extremely high availability, which can be interacted with over the internet via REST APIs, a CLI or the AWS console.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] AWS services are delivered to customers via a network of AWS server farms located throughout the world.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] Fees are based on a combination of usage (known as a "Pay-as-you-go" model), hardware, operating system, software, and networking features chosen by the subscriber requiring various degrees of availability, redundancy, security, and service options.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] Subscribers can pay for a single virtual AWS computer, a dedicated physical computer, or clusters of either.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] Amazon provides select portions of security for subscribers (e.g. physical security of the data centers) while other aspects of security are the responsibility of the subscriber (e.g. account management, vulnerability scanning, patching).
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] AWS operates from many global geographical regions, including nine in North America.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] Amazon markets AWS to subscribers as a way of obtaining large-scale computing capacity more quickly and cheaply than building an actual physical server farm.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] All services are billed based on usage, but each service measures usage in varying ways.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] As of 2023 Q1, AWS has 31% market share for cloud infrastructure while the next two competitors Microsoft Azure and Google Cloud have 25%, and 11% respectively, according to Synergy Research Group.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] As of 2025 AWS comprises over 200 products and services including computing, storage, networking, database, analytics, application services, deployment, management, machine learning, mobile, developer tools, RobOps and tools for the Internet of Things.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] The most popular include Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), Amazon Simple Storage Service (Amazon S3), Amazon Connect, and AWS Lambda (a serverless function that can perform arbitrary code written in any language that can be configured to be triggered by hundreds of events, including HTTP calls).
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] Services expose functionality through APIs for clients to use in their applications.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] These APIs are accessed over HTTP, using the REST architectural style and SOAP protocol for older APIs and exclusively JSON for newer ones.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] Clients can interact with these APIs in various ways, including from the AWS console (a website), by using SDKs written in various languages (such as Python, Java, and JavaScript), or by making direct REST calls.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] The genesis of AWS came in the early 2000s.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] After building *Merchant.com*, Amazon's e-commerce-as-a-service platform that offers third-party retailers a way to build their own web-stores, Amazon pursued service-oriented architecture as a means to scale its engineering operations, led by then CTO Allan Vermeulen.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] He also called for increasing the percentage of the time engineers spent building the software rather than doing other tasks.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] Amazon created "a shared IT platform" so its engineering organizations, which were spending 70% of their time on "undifferentiated heavy-lifting" such as IT and infrastructure problems, could focus on customer-facing innovation instead.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] In July 2002 Amazon.com Web Services, managed by Colin Bryar, launched its first web services, opening up the Amazon.com platform to all developers.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] Over one hundred applications were built on top of it by 2004.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] This unexpected developer interest took Amazon by surprise and convinced them that developers were "hungry for more".
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] By the summer of 2003, Andy Jassy had taken over Bryar's portfolio at Rick Dalzell's behest, after Vermeulen, who was Bezos' first pick, declined the offer.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] Jassy subsequently mapped out the vision for an "Internet OS" made up of foundational infrastructure primitives that alleviated key impediments to shipping software applications faster.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] By fall 2003, databases, storage, and compute were identified as the first set of infrastructure pieces that Amazon should launch.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] According to Brewster Kahle, co-founder of Alexa Internet, which was acquired by Amazon in 1999, his start-up's compute infrastructure helped Amazon solve its big data problems and later informed the innovations that underpinned AWS.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] Jassy assembled a founding team of 57 employees from a mix of engineering and business backgrounds to kick-start these initiatives, with a majority of the hires coming from outside the company.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] They included Jeff Lawson, the Twilio CEO; Adam Selipsky, the Tableau CEO; and Mikhail Seregine, a co-founder at Outschool.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] Near the end of their paper, they mentioned the possibility of selling access to virtual servers as a service, proposing the company could generate revenue from the new infrastructure investment.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] Thereafter Pinkham, Willem van Biljon, and lead developer Christopher Brown developed the Amazon EC2 service, with a team in Cape Town, South Africa.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] In October 2004, Amazon released Alexa Web Information Service (AWIS) as beta.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] In November 2004, AWS launched its first infrastructure service, as beta: Simple Queue Service (SQS)., and officially launched in July 2006.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] On March 14, 2006, AWS launched Amazon S3 cloud storage, and that was the first AWS' IaaS that was generally available, followed by EC2 in August 2006.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] Pi Corporation, a startup Paul Maritz co-founded, was the first beta-user of EC2 outside of Amazon, while Microsoft was among EC2's first enterprise customers.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] Later that year SmugMug, one of the early AWS adopters, attributed savings of around US$400,000 in storage costs to S3.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] According to Vogels, S3 was built with 8 microservices when it launched in 2006 and had over 300 microservices by 2022.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] In September 2007, AWS announced its annual *Start-up Challenge*, a contest with prizes worth $100,000 for entrepreneurs and software developers in the US using AWS services such as S3 and EC2 to build their businesses.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] The first edition saw participation from Justin.tv, which Amazon later acquired in 2014.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] Ooyala, an online media company, was the eventual winner.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] AWS offers, as of June 16, 2022, two block-storage options: the EC2 Instance Store and the Elastic Block Store (EBS).
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] Additional AWS services from this period include SimpleDB, Mechanical Turk, Elastic Beanstalk, Relational Database Service, DynamoDB, CloudWatch, Simple Workflow, CloudFront, and Availability Zones.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] In November 2010, it was reported that all of Amazon.com's retail sites had migrated to AWS.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] Prior to 2012, AWS was considered a part of Amazon.com and so its revenue was not delineated in Amazon financial statements.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] In that year industry watchers for the first time estimated AWS revenue to be over $1.5 billion.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] On November 27, 2012, AWS hosted its first major annual conference, *re:Invent* with a focus on AWS's partners and ecosystem, with over 150 sessions.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] The three-day event was held in Las Vegas because of its relatively cheaper connectivity with locations across the United States and the rest of the world.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] Andy Jassy and Werner Vogels presented keynotes, with Jeff Bezos joining Vogels for a fireside chat.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] AWS opened early registrations at US$1,099 per head for their customers from over 190 countries.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] On stage with Andy Jassy at the event which saw around 6000 attendees, Reed Hastings, CEO at Netflix, announced plans to migrate 100% of Netflix's infrastructure to AWS.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] To support industry-wide training and skills standardization, AWS began offering a certification program for computer engineers, on April 30, 2013, to highlight expertise in cloud computing.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] Later that year, in October, AWS launched *Activate*, a program for start-ups worldwide to leverage AWS credits, third-party integrations, and free access to AWS experts to help build their business.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] In 2014, AWS launched its partner network, AWS Partner Network (APN), which is focused on helping AWS-based companies grow and scale the success of their business with close collaboration and best practices.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] In October 2014, Amazon Aurora was launched.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] In January 2015, Amazon Web Services acquired Annapurna Labs, an Israel-based microelectronics company for a reported US$350–370M.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] In April 2015, Amazon.com reported AWS was profitable, with sales of $1.57 billion in the first quarter of the year and $265 million of operating income.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] Founder Jeff Bezos described it as a fast-growing $5 billion business; analysts described it as "surprisingly more profitable than forecast".
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] In October, Amazon.com said in its Q3 earnings report that AWS's operating income was $521 million, with operating margins at 25 percent.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] AWS's 2015 Q3 revenue was $2.1 billion, a 78% increase from 2014's Q3 revenue of $1.17 billion.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] 2015 Q4 revenue for the AWS segment increased 69.5% y/y to $2.4 billion with a 28.5% operating margin, giving AWS a $9.6 billion run rate.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] In 2015, Gartner estimated that AWS customers are deploying 10x more infrastructure on AWS than the combined adoption of the next 14 providers.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] In 2016 Q1, revenue was $2.57 billion with net income of $604 million, a 64% increase over 2015 Q1 that resulted in AWS being more profitable than Amazon's North American retail business for the first time.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] Jassy was thereafter promoted to CEO of the division.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] Around the same time, Amazon experienced a 42% rise in stock value as a result of increased earnings, of which AWS contributed 56% to corporate profits.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] AWS had $17.46 billion in annual revenue in 2017.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] By the end of 2020, the number had grown to $46 billion.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] Reflecting the success of AWS, Jassy's annual compensation in 2017 hit nearly $36 million.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] In January 2018, Amazon launched a unified autoscaling service on AWS.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] This new service unifies and builds on AWS existing, service-specific, scaling features like EC2 Auto Scaling groups, that was launched in August 2006.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] In November 2018, AWS announced customized ARM cores for use in its servers.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] Also in November 2018, AWS created ground stations to communicate with customers' satellites.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] In 2019, AWS reported 37% yearly growth and accounted for 12% of Amazon's revenue (up from 11% in 2018).
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] In April 2021, AWS reported 32% yearly growth and accounted for 32% of $41.8 billion cloud market in Q1 2021.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] In January 2022, AWS joined the MACH Alliance, a non-profit enterprise technology advocacy group.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] In June 2022, it was reported that in 2019 Capital One had not secured their AWS resources properly, and was subject to a data breach by a former AWS employee.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] The employee was convicted of hacking into the company's cloud servers to steal customer data and use computer power to mine cryptocurrency.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] The ex-employee was able to download the personal information of more than 100 million Capital One customers.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] In June 2022, AWS announced they had launched the AWS Snowcone, a small computing device, to the International Space Station on the Axiom Mission 1.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] In September 2023, AWS announced it would become AI startup Anthropic's primary cloud provider.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] Amazon has committed to investing up to $4 billion in Anthropic and will have a minority ownership position in the company.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] In April 2024, AWS announced a new service called Deadline Cloud, which lets customers set up, deploy and scale up graphics and visual effects rendering pipelines on AWS cloud infrastructure.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] In July 2024, AWS won a $1.3 billion (A$2 billion) contract with Australia's government to build a top-secret cloud service.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] The service included a partnership with the Australian Signals Directorate (ASD).
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] The ASD director general Rachel Noble said the service would "provide a state-of-the-art collaborative space for our intelligence and defense community to store and access top-secret data”.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] In December 2024, AWS announced Amazon Nova, its own family of foundation models.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] These models, offered through Amazon Bedrock, are designed for various tasks including content generation, video understanding, and building agentic applications.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] They are available in six different sizes.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] In March and April of 2026, during the 2026 Iran War, Iranian drone and missile strikes damaged AWS data centers in the United Arab Emirates (me-central-1) and Bahrain (me-south-1) regions, in the first deliberate military targeting of a commercial data center.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] Iran claimed the data centers hosted US military workloads.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] AWS advised customers to migrate to other regions.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] In October 2013, AWS was awarded a $600M contract with the CIA.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] By 2019, it was reported that more than 80% of Germany's listed DAX companies used AWS.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] Navy said it moved 72,000 users from six commands to an AWS cloud system as a first step toward pushing all of its data and analytics onto the cloud.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] In January 2021, Amazon announced that it would suspend Parler from Amazon Web Services, stating Parler hosted “violent content” that violates its terms of service.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] Later in 2021, DISH Network announced it would develop and launch its 5G network on AWS.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] It was also reported that spy agencies and government departments in the UK, such as GCHQ, MI5, MI6, and the Ministry of Defence, contracted AWS to host their classified materials.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] In 2022, Amazon shared a $9 billion contract from the United States Department of Defense for cloud computing with Google, Microsoft, and Oracle.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] AWS won a $581 million contract from the U.S.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] Air Force in January 2026 to provide cloud services and specific Amazon data centers as part of the Cloud One Program, the Air Force's enterprise cloud environment.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] Multiple financial services firms have shifted to AWS in some form.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] Notable customers include NASA and the Obama presidential campaign of 2012.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] As of October 2025, AWS has distinct operations in 38 geographical "regions": nine in North America, two in South America, nine in Europe, four in the Middle East, one in Africa, thirteen in the Asia–Pacific, and three in Australia and New Zealand.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] Most AWS regions are enabled by default for AWS accounts.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] Regions introduced after 20 March 2019 are considered to be *opt-in* regions, requiring a user to explicitly enable them in order for the region to be usable in the account.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] For opt-in regions, Identity and Access Management (IAM) resources such as users and roles are only propagated to the regions that are enabled.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] Each region is wholly contained within a single country and all of its data and services stay within the designated region.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] Each region has multiple "Availability Zones", which consist of one or more discrete data centers, each with redundant power, networking, and connectivity, housed in separate facilities.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] Availability Zones do not automatically provide additional scalability or redundancy within a region, since they are intentionally isolated from each other to prevent outages from spreading between zones.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] Several services can operate across Availability Zones (e.g., S3, DynamoDB) while others can be configured to replicate across zones to spread demand and avoid downtime from failures.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] As of December 2014, Amazon Web Services operated an estimated 1.4 million servers across 11 regions and 28 availability zones.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] As of March 2024, AWS had announced the planned launch of six additional regions in Malaysia, Mexico, New Zealand, Thailand, Saudi Arabia, and the European Union.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] In mid March 2023, Amazon Web Services signed a cooperation agreement with the New Zealand Government to build large data centers in New Zealand.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] AWS also has "pop-up lofts" in different locations around the world.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] These market AWS to entrepreneurs and startups in different tech industries in a physical location.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] Visitors can work or relax inside the loft, or learn more about what they can do with AWS.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] In June 2014, AWS opened their first temporary pop-up loft in San Francisco.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] In May 2015 they expanded to New York City, and in September 2015 expanded to Berlin.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] AWS opened its fourth location, in Tel Aviv from March 1, 2016, to March 22, 2016.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] A pop-up loft was open in London from September 10 to October 29, 2015.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] The pop-up lofts in New York and San Francisco are indefinitely closed due to the COVID-19 pandemic while Tokyo has remained open in a limited capacity.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] In 2017, AWS launched AWS re/Start in the United Kingdom to help young adults and military veterans retrain in technology-related skills.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] In partnership with the Prince's Trust and the Ministry of Defence (MoD), AWS will help to provide re-training opportunities for young people from disadvantaged backgrounds and former military personnel.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] AWS is working alongside a number of partner companies including Cloudreach, Sage Group, EDF Energy, and Tesco Bank.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] In April 2022, AWS announced that the organization had committed more than $30 million over three years to early-stage start-ups led by Black, Latino, LGBTQIA+, and women founders as part of its AWS impact Accelerator.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] The Initiative offers qualifying start-ups up to $225,000 in cash, credits, extensive training, mentoring, technical guidance and includes up to $100,000 in AWS service credits.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] In 2014, AWS claimed its aim was to achieve 100% renewable energy usage in the future.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] In 2016, Greenpeace assessed major tech companies—including cloud services providers like AWS, Microsoft, Oracle, Google, IBM, Salesforce and Rackspace—based on their level of "clean energy" usage.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] Greenpeace evaluated companies on their mix of renewable-energy sources; transparency; renewable-energy commitment and policies; energy efficiency and greenhouse-gas mitigation; renewable-energy procurement; and advocacy.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] The group gave AWS an overall "C" grade.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] Greenpeace credited AWS for its advances toward greener computing in recent years and its plans to launch multiple wind and solar farms across the United States.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] The organization stated that Amazon is opaque about its carbon footprint.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] In January 2021, AWS joined an industry pledge to achieve climate neutrality of data centers by 2030, the Climate Neutral Data Centre Pact.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] As of 2023, Amazon as a whole is the largest corporate purchaser of renewable energy in the world, a position it has held since 2020, and has a global portfolio of over 20 GW of renewable energy capacity.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] In 2022, 90% of all Amazon operations, including data centers, were powered by renewables.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] In 2024, AWS paid $650 million for a data center at the 2.5 GW Susquehanna nuclear power plant, connected at 300 MW.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] The power increase depends on Amazon's expansion of the data center.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] US Department of Homeland Security has employed the software ATLAS, which runs on Amazon Cloud.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] It scanned more than 16.5 million records of naturalized Americans and flagged approximately 124,000 of them for manual analysis and review by USCIS officers regarding denaturalization.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] Some of the scanned data came from the Terrorist Screening Database and the National Crime Information Center.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] The algorithm and the criteria for the algorithm were secret.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] Amazon faced protests from its own employees and activists for the anti-migrant collaboration with authorities.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] The contract for Project Nimbus drew rebuke and condemnation from the companies' shareholders as well as their employees, over concerns that the project would lead to abuses of Palestinians' human rights in the context of the ongoing occupation and the Israeli–Palestinian conflict.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] Specifically, they voice concern over how the technology will enable further surveillance of Palestinians and unlawful data collection on them as well as facilitate the expansion of Israel's illegal settlements on Palestinian land.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] A government procurement document featuring 'obligatory customers' of Nimbus, including "two of Israel’s leading state-owned weapons manufacturers" Israel Aerospace Industries and Rafael Advanced Defense Systems, was published in 2021 with periodic updates since (up to Oct 2023).
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] AWS has been noted to work with Chinese companies under varying degrees of U.S. government sanctions, such as Hikvision and Dahua Technology, which have been accused to enabling mass surveillance and human rights abuses in China and elsewhere.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] In July 2025, a security researcher disclosed a supply-chain vulnerability in the Amazon Q Developer Extension (version 1.84) for Visual Studio Code.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] The issue involved a malicious pull request to the project's GitHub repository, which introduced a prompt instructing the AI assistant to delete local files and AWS resources.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] AWS acknowledged the issue in Security Bulletin AWS‑2025‑015 and released version 1.85 to remove the injected prompt.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] The company stated that no customer systems or data were affected.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] However, critics including Corey Quinn, writing in Last Week in AWS, questioned the transparency of the response, noting the absence of a changelog entry, a CVE assignment, or a public statement beyond the bulletin.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] In response to the Log4Shell vulnerability, AWS released hot patch solutions to mitigate risks in Java applications across various environments, including standalone servers, Kubernetes clusters, and Elastic Container Service (ECS).
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] These patches were designed for both AWS and non-AWS environments.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] However, researchers from Unit 42 at Palo Alto Networks identified critical security flaws in these patches that could be exploited for container escape and privilege escalation, potentially granting attackers unauthorized root-level access to the host system.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] AWS addressed these vulnerabilities by releasing updated patches on April 19, 2022.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] Users who deployed the initial patches were advised to upgrade to the latest versions to mitigate security risks.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] In April 2024, security researchers from Miggo security identified a configuration vulnerability in AWS Application Load Balancer (ALB) that could allow attackers to bypass access controls and compromise web applications.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] The issue stemmed from how some users configured ALB's authentication handoff to third-party services, potentially enabling unauthorized access to application data.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] On July 11, 2024, AWS confirmed the issue affecting its customers, and on July 19, 2024, AWS updated its documentation accordingly to recommend more secure implementation practices.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] In 2026, Amazon Web Services (AWS) data center infrastructure in the United Arab Emirates and Bahrain experienced service disruptions following reported drone strikes in the region.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] AWS applies charges for data transferred both between Availability Zones within the same region (inter-AZ) and across different geographic regions (inter-region).
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] The pricing structure is influenced by several factors, including the source and destination of the data, the specific AWS services in use, and the underlying networking architecture.
[src:aws-s3/amazon-web-services] Various services implement different data transfer models, and the choice of communication method—such as VPC Peering, Transit Gateway, or AWS PrivateLink—can also affect the overall cost.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] Cloud storage services may be accessed through a colocated cloud computing service, a web service application programming interface (API) or by applications that use the API, such as cloud desktop storage, a cloud storage gateway or Web-based content management systems.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] Cloud computing is believed to have been invented by J.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] Licklider in the 1960s with his work on ARPANET to connect people and data from anywhere at any time.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] In 1983, CompuServe offered its consumer users a small amount of disk space that could be used to store any files they chose to upload.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] In 1994, AT&T launched PersonaLink Services, an online platform for personal and business communication and entrepreneurship.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] In 2005, Box announced an online file sharing and personal cloud content management service for businesses.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] Alibaba Cloud was launched in September 2009, three years after AWS.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] As of 2024, Gartner ranked cloud storage platforms as follows: AWS, Google, Microsoft, Oracle, Alibaba, IBM, Huawei and Tencent.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] These account for 97% of the global cloud services market.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] This rating was based on ability to execute in market and innovation vision.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] In 2023, 80% of China's technology companies and half of AI LLM companies ran on Alibaba Cloud while in the US dominance belonged to AWS with 31 to 50% share.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] In 2026, Alibaba is scheduled to spend more than 300 million yuan, about $52 billion, on artificial intelligence and cloud infrastructure over the next three years, a figure much larger than the amount spent the previous year.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] Data centers will also be expanding, and AI models like Qwen.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] Alibaba's CEO, Eddie Wu, describes the amount spent as the largest to date on cloud and AI.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] Also, he explained that they expect much of the internal AI workload to run on Alibaba Cloud.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] Spending will include specific items such as GPU-like accelerators and large-scale data centers to support internal workloads and external client functions, underscoring Alibaba's pivot from e-commerce to cloud infrastructure.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] Cloud storage is based on highly virtualized infrastructure and is like broader cloud computing in terms of interfaces, near-instant elasticity and scalability, multi-tenancy, and metered resources.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] Cloud storage services can be used from an off-premises service (Amazon S3) or deployed on-premises (ViON Capacity Services).
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] There are three types of cloud storage: a hosted object storage service, file storage, and block storage.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] Each of these cloud storage types offer their own unique advantages.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] Security of stored data and data in transit may be a concern when storing sensitive data at a cloud storage provider.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] Outsourcing data storage increases the attack surface area.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] Cloud storage is a rich resource for both hackers and national security agencies.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] Because the cloud holds data from many different users and organizations, hackers see it as a very valuable target.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] The number of people with access to the data who could be compromised (e.g., bribed, or coerced) increases dramatically.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] Decryption keys that are kept by the service user, as opposed to the service provider, limit access to data by service provider employees.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] As for sharing multiple data in the cloud with multiple users, a large number of keys has to be distributed to users via secure channels for decryption, also it has to be securely stored and managed by the users in their devices.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] Storing these keys requires rather expensive secure storage.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] To overcome that, key-aggregate cryptosystem can be used.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] It increases the number of networks over which the data travels.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] Instead of just a local area network (LAN) or storage area network (SAN), data stored on a cloud requires a WAN (wide area network) to connect them both.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] By sharing storage and networks with many other users/customers it is possible for other customers to access your data.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] Sometimes because of erroneous actions, faulty equipment, a bug and sometimes because of criminal intent.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] This risk applies to all types of storage and not only cloud storage.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] The risk of having data read during transmission can be mitigated through encryption technology.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] Encryption in transit protects data as it is being transmitted to and from the cloud service.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] Encryption at rest protects data that is stored at the service provider.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] Encrypting data in an on-premises cloud service on-ramp system can provide both kinds of encryption protection.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] There are several options available to avoid security issues.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] One option is to use a private cloud instead of a public cloud.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] Another option is to ingest data in an encrypted format where the key is held within the on-premise infrastructure.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] To this end, access is often by use of on-premise cloud storage gateways that have options to encrypt the data prior to transfer.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] Typically, cloud storage Service Level Agreements (SLAs) do not encompass all forms of service interruptions.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] Exclusions typically include planned maintenance, downtime resulting from external factors such as network issues, human errors like misconfigurations, natural disasters, force majeure events, or security breaches.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] Typically, customers bear the responsibility of monitoring SLA compliance and must file claims for any unmet SLAs within a designated timeframe.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] Customers should be aware of how deviations from SLAs are calculated, as these parameters may vary by other services offered within the same provider.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] These requirements can place a considerable burden on customers.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] Additionally, SLA percentages and conditions can differ across various services within the same provider, with some services lacking any SLA altogether.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] In cases of service interruptions due to hardware failures in the cloud provider, service providers typically do not offer monetary compensation.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] Instead, eligible users may receive credits as outlined in the corresponding SLA.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] Hybrid cloud storage is a term for a storage infrastructure that uses a combination of on-premises storage resources with cloud storage.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] The on-premises storage is usually managed by the organization, while the public cloud storage provider is responsible for the management and security of the data stored in the cloud.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] Hybrid cloud storage can be implemented by an on-premises cloud storage gateway that presents a file system or object storage interface that users can access in the same way they would access a local storage system.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] The cloud storage gateway transparently transfers the data to and from the cloud storage service, providing low latency access to the data through a local cache.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] Hybrid cloud storage can be used to supplement an organization's internal storage resources, or it can be used as the primary storage infrastructure.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] In either case, hybrid cloud storage can provide organizations with greater flexibility and scalability than traditional on-premises storage infrastructure.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] There are several benefits to using hybrid cloud storage, including the ability to cache frequently used data on-site for quick access, while inactive cold data is stored off-site in the cloud.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] This can save space, reduce storage costs and improve performance.
[src:aws-s3/cloud-storage] Additionally, hybrid cloud storage can provide organizations with greater redundancy and fault tolerance, as data is stored in both on-premises and cloud storage infrastructure.
[src:aws-s3/data-lake] A **data lake** is a system or repository of data stored in its natural, raw format, usually object blobs or files.
[src:aws-s3/data-lake] A data lake is usually a single store of data including raw copies of source system data, sensor data, social data etc., and transformed data used for tasks such as reporting, visualization, advanced analytics, and machine learning.
[src:aws-s3/data-lake] A data lake can include structured data from relational databases (rows and columns), semi-structured data (CSV, logs, XML, JSON), unstructured data (emails, documents, PDFs), and binary data (images, audio, video).
[src:aws-s3/data-lake] A data lake can be established *on premises* (within an organization's data centers) or *in the cloud* (using cloud services).
[src:aws-s3/data-lake] James Dixon, then chief technology officer at Pentaho, coined the term by 2011 to contrast it with data mart, which is a smaller repository of interesting attributes derived from raw data.
[src:aws-s3/data-lake] In promoting data lakes, he argued that data marts have several inherent problems, such as information siloing.
[src:aws-s3/data-lake] PricewaterhouseCoopers (PwC) said that data lakes could "put an end to data silos".
[src:aws-s3/data-lake] Many companies use cloud storage services such as Google Cloud Storage and Amazon S3 or a distributed file system such as Apache Hadoop distributed file system (HDFS).
[src:aws-s3/data-lake] There is a gradual academic interest in the concept of data lakes.
[src:aws-s3/data-lake] For example, Personal DataLake at Cardiff University is a new type of data lake which aims at managing big data of individual users by providing a single point of collecting, organizing, and sharing personal data.
[src:aws-s3/data-lake] Early data lakes, such as Hadoop 1.0, had limited capabilities because it only supported batch-oriented processing (Map Reduce).
[src:aws-s3/data-lake] Interacting with it required expertise in Java, map reduce and higher-level tools like Apache Pig, Apache Spark and Apache Hive (which were also originally batch-oriented).
[src:aws-s3/data-lake] Poorly managed data lakes have been facetiously called data swamps.
[src:aws-s3/data-lake] In June 2015, David Needle characterized "so-called data lakes" as "one of the more controversial ways to manage big data".
[src:aws-s3/data-lake] PwC was also careful to note in their research that not all data lake initiatives are successful.
[src:aws-s3/data-lake] They describe companies that build successful data lakes as gradually maturing their lake as they figure out which data and metadata are important to the organization.
[src:aws-s3/data-lake] Another criticism is that the term *data lake* is used with many different meanings.
[src:aws-s3/data-lake] It may be used to refer to, for example: any tools or data management practices that are not data warehouses; a particular technology for implementation; a raw data reservoir; a hub for ETL offload; or a central hub for self-service analytics.
[src:aws-s3/data-lake] While critiques of data lakes are warranted, in many cases they apply to other data projects as well.
[src:aws-s3/data-lake] For example, the definition of *data warehouse* is also changeable, and not all data warehouse efforts have been successful.
[src:aws-s3/data-lake] In response to various critiques, McKinsey noted that the data lake should be viewed as a service model for delivering business value within the enterprise, not a technology outcome.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] The concept of data management emerged alongside the evolution of computing technology.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] In the 1950s, as computers became more prevalent, organizations began to grapple with the challenge of organizing and storing data efficiently.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] Early methods relied on punch cards and manual sorting, which were labor-intensive and prone to errors.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] The introduction of database management systems in the 1970s marked a significant milestone, enabling structured storage and retrieval of data.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] By the 1980s, relational database models revolutionized data management, emphasizing the importance of data as an asset and fostering a data-centric mindset in business.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] This era also saw the rise of data governance practices, which prioritized the organization and regulation of data to ensure quality and compliance.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] Over time, advancements in technology, such as cloud computing and big data analytics, have further refined data management, making it a cornerstone of modern business operations.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] As of 2025, data management encompasses a wide range of practices, from data storage and security to analytics and decision-making, reflecting its critical role in driving innovation and efficiency across industries.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] The Data Management Body of Knowledge, DMBoK, developed by the Data Management Association, DAMA, outlines key knowledge areas that serve as the foundation for modern data management practices, suggesting a framework for organizations to manage data as a strategic asset.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] Data governance refers to the policies, procedures, and standards that ensure data is managed consistently and responsibly across an organization.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] In enterprise contexts, governance involves aligning stakeholders across business units, defining data ownership, and quantifying the benefits of improved data quality.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] Effective governance frameworks often include data stewardship roles, escalation protocols, and cross-functional oversight committees to maintain trust and accountability in data use.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] Data architecture consist of models, policies, rules, and standards that govern which data is collected and how it is stored, arranged, integrated, and put to use in data systems and in organizations.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] Data is usually one of several architecture domains that form the pillars of an enterprise architecture or solution architecture.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] Data Architecture focuses on designing the overall structure of data systems.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] It ensures that data flows are efficient and that systems are scalable, adaptable, and aligned with business needs.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] This area centers on creating models that logically represent data relationships.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] It’s essential for both designing databases and ensuring that data is structured in a way that facilitates analysis and reporting.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] Deals with the physical storage of data and its day-to-day management.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] This includes everything from traditional data centers to cloud-based storage solutions and ensuring efficient data processing.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] Ensures that data from various sources can be seamlessly shared and combined across multiple systems, which is critical for comprehensive analytics and decision-making.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] Focuses on managing unstructured data such as documents, multimedia, and other content, ensuring that it is stored, categorized, and easily retrievable.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] Involves consolidating data into repositories that support analytics, reporting, and business insights.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] In computing, a data warehouse (DW or DWH), also known as an enterprise data warehouse (EDW), is a system used for reporting and data analysis and is a core component of business intelligence.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] Data warehouses are central repositories of data integrated from disparate sources.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] They store current and historical data organized in a way that is optimized for data analysis, generation of reports, and developing insights across the integrated data.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] They are intended to be used by analysts and managers to help make organizational decisions.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] Business intelligence (BI) consists of strategies, methodologies, and technologies used by enterprises for data analysis and management of business information to inform business strategies and business operations.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] Common functions of BI technologies include reporting, online analytical processing, analytics, dashboard development, data mining, process mining, complex event processing, business performance management, benchmarking, text mining, predictive analytics, and prescriptive analytics.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] A data mart is a structure/access pattern specific to *data warehouse* environments.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] The data mart is a subset of the data warehouse that focuses on a specific business line, department, subject area, or team.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] Whereas data warehouses have an enterprise-wide depth, the information in data marts pertains to a single department.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] In some deployments, each department or business unit is considered the *owner* of its data mart, including all the *hardware*, *software*, and *data*.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] This enables each department to isolate the use, manipulation, and development of their data.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] In other deployments where conformed dimensions are used, this business unit ownership will not hold true for shared dimensions like customer, product, etc.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] Data analysis is the process of inspecting, cleansing, transforming, and modeling data with the goal of discovering useful information, informing conclusions, and supporting decision-making.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] Data analysis has multiple facets and approaches, encompassing diverse techniques under a variety of names, and is used in different business, science, and social science domains.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] In today's business world, data analysis plays an important role in making decisions more scientific and helping businesses operate more effectively.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] It is widely used in fields such as business analytics, healthcare, and artificial intelligence to extract meaningful insights from data.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] Data mining is the process of extracting and finding patterns in massive data sets involving methods at the intersection of machine learning, statistics, and database systems.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] Data mining is an interdisciplinary subfield of computer science and statistics with an overall goal of extracting information (with intelligent methods) from a data set and transforming the information into a comprehensible structure for further use.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] Data mining is the analysis step of the "knowledge discovery in databases" process, or KDD.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] Aside from the raw analysis step, it also involves database and data management aspects, data pre-processing, model and inference considerations, interestingness metrics, complexity considerations, post-processing of discovered structures, visualization, and online updating.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] A data scientist is a professional who creates programming code and combines it with statistical knowledge to summarize data.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] Manages data about data, including definitions, origin, and usage, to enhance the understanding and usability of the organization’s data assets.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] Data quality is not only a technical concern but a strategic enabler of trust, compliance, and decision-making.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] High-quality data supports consistent reporting, regulatory adherence, and customer confidence.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] Enterprise data management programs often define quality metrics such as precision, granularity, and timeliness, and link these to business outcomes.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] Reference data comprises standardized codes and values for consistent interpretation across systems.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] Master data management (MDM) governs and centralizes an organization’s critical data, ensuring a unified, reliable information source that supports effective decision-making and operational efficiency.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] Data security refers to a comprehensive set of practices and technologies designed to protect digital information and systems from unauthorized access, use, disclosure, modification, or destruction.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] It encompasses encryption, access controls, monitoring, and risk assessments to maintain data integrity, confidentiality, and availability.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] Data privacy involves safeguarding individuals’ personal information by ensuring its collection, storage, and use comply with consent, legal standards, and confidentiality principles.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] It emphasizes protecting sensitive data from misuse or unauthorized access while respecting users' rights.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] The distinction between data and derived value is illustrated by the "information ladder" or the DIKAR model.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] The "DIKAR" model stands for Data, Information, Knowledge, Action, and Result.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] It is a framework used to bridge the gap between raw data and actionable outcomes.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] The model emphasizes the transformation of data into information, which is then interpreted to create knowledge.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] This knowledge guides actions that lead to measurable results.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] DIKAR is widely applied in organizational strategies, helping businesses align their data management processes with decision-making and performance goals.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] By focusing on each stage, the model ensures that data is effectively utilized to drive informed decisions and achieve desired outcomes.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] It is particularly valuable in technology-driven environments.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] The "information ladder" illustrates the progression from data (raw facts) to information (processed data), knowledge (interpreted information), and ultimately wisdom (applied knowledge).
[src:aws-s3/data-management] Each step adds value and context, enabling better decision-making.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] It emphasizes the transformation of unstructured inputs into meaningful insights for practical use.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] In research, Data management refers to the systematic process of handling data throughout its lifecycle.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] This includes activities such as collecting, organizing, storing, analyzing, and sharing data to ensure its accuracy, accessibility, and security.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] A Data Management Plan (DMP) is a structured document that outlines how research data will be collected, organized, stored, shared, and preserved throughout and after a research project.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] It serves as a guide to ensure that data are handled responsibly, remain accessible, and are protected from loss or misuse.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] Effective data management also involves creating a data management plan, DMP, addressing issues like ethical considerations, compliance with regulatory standards, and long-term preservation.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] Proper management enhances research transparency, reproducibility, and the efficient use of resources, ultimately contributing to the credibility and impact of research findings.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] It is a critical practice across disciplines to ensure data integrity and usability both during and after a research project.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] Big data refers to the collection and analyses of massive sets of data.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] While big data is a recent phenomenon, the requirement for data to aid decision-making traces back to the early 1970s with the emergence of decision support systems (DSS).
[src:aws-s3/data-management] These systems can be considered as the initial iteration of data management for decision support.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] Studies indicate that customer transactions account for a 40% increase in the data collected annually, which means that financial data has a considerable impact on business decisions.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] Therefore, modern organizations are using big data analytics to identify 5 to 10 new data sources that can help them collect and analyze data for improved decision-making.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] Jonsen (2013) explains that organizations using average analytics technologies are 20% more likely to gain higher returns compared to their competitors who have not introduced any analytics capabilities in their operations.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] Also, IRI reported that the retail industry could experience an increase of more than $10 billion each year resulting from the implementation of modern analytics technologies.
[src:aws-s3/data-management] Therefore, the following hypothesis can be proposed: Economic and financial outcomes can impact how organizations use data analytics tools.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] Object storage systems allow retention of massive amounts of unstructured data in which data is written once and read once (or many times).
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] Object storage is used for purposes such as storing objects like videos and photos on Facebook, songs on Spotify, or files in online collaboration services, such as Dropbox.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] One of the limitations with object storage is that it is not intended for transactional data, as object storage was not designed to replace NAS file access and sharing; it does not support the locking and sharing mechanisms needed to maintain a single, accurately updated version of a file.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] Jim Starkey coined the term ***blob*** working at Digital Equipment Corporation to refer to opaque data entities.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] The terminology was adopted for Rdb/VMS.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] *Blob* is often humorously explained to be an abbreviation for *binary large object*.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] According to Starkey, this backronym arose when Terry McKiever, working in marketing at Apollo Computer felt that the term needed to be an abbreviation.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] McKiever began using the expansion *basic large object*.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] This was later eclipsed by the retroactive explanation of blobs as *binary large objects*.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] According to Starkey, "Blob don't stand for nothin'." Rejecting the acronym, he explained his motivation behind the coinage, saying, "A blob is the thing that ate Cincinnatti [*sic*], Cleveland, or whatever", referring to the 1958 science fiction film *The Blob*.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] In 1995, research led by Garth Gibson on Network-Attached Secure Disks first promoted the concept of splitting less common operations, like namespace manipulations, from common operations, like reads and writes, to optimize the performance and scale of both.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] In the same year, a Belgian company – FilePool – was established to build the basis for archiving functions.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] Object storage was proposed at Gibson's Carnegie Mellon University lab as a research project in 1996.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] Another key concept was abstracting the writes and reads of data to more flexible data containers (objects).
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] Fine grained access control through object storage architecture was further described by one of the NASD team, Howard Gobioff, who later was one of the inventors of the Google File System.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] Other related work includes the Coda filesystem project at Carnegie Mellon, which started in 1987, and spawned the Lustre file system.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] There is also the OceanStore project at UC Berkeley, which started in 1999 and the Logistical Networking project at the University of Tennessee Knoxville, which started in 1998.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] In 1999, Gibson founded Panasas to commercialize the concepts developed by the NASD team.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] Seagate Technology played a central role in the development of object storage.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] This paper was proposed to INCITS T-10 (International Committee for Information Technology Standards) with a goal to form a committee and design a specification based on the SCSI interface protocol.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] This defined objects as abstracted data, with unique identifiers and metadata, how objects related to file systems, along with many other innovative concepts.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] Anderson presented many of these ideas at the SNIA conference in October 1999.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] The presentation revealed an IP Agreement that had been signed in February 1997 between the original collaborators (with Seagate represented by Anderson and Chris Malakapalli) and covered the benefits of object storage, scalable computing, platform independence, and storage management.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] One of the design principles of object storage is to abstract some of the lower layers of storage away from the administrators and applications.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] Thus, data is exposed and managed as objects instead of blocks or (exclusively) files.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] Objects contain additional descriptive properties which can be used for better indexing or management.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] Administrators do not have to perform lower-level storage functions like constructing and managing logical volumes to utilize disk capacity or setting RAID levels to deal with disk failure.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] Object storage also allows the addressing and identification of individual objects by more than just file name and file path.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] Object storage adds a unique identifier within a bucket, or across the entire system, to support much larger namespaces and eliminate name collisions.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] Object storage explicitly separates file metadata from data to support additional capabilities.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] Object storage provides programmatic interfaces to allow applications to manipulate data.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] At the base level, this includes Create, read, update and delete (CRUD) functions for basic read, write and delete operations.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] Some object storage implementations go further, supporting additional functionality like object/file versioning, object replication, life-cycle management and movement of objects between different tiers and types of storage.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] Most API implementations are REST-based, allowing the use of many standard HTTP calls.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] The vast majority of cloud storage available in the market leverages an object-storage architecture.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] Some notable examples are Amazon S3, which debuted in March 2006, Microsoft Azure Blob Storage, IBM Cloud Object Storage, Rackspace Cloud Files (whose code was donated in 2010 to Openstack project and released as OpenStack Swift), and Google Cloud Storage released in May 2010.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] Some distributed file systems use an object-based architecture, where file metadata is stored in metadata servers and file data is stored in object storage servers.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] File system client software interacts with the distinct servers, and abstracts them to present a full file system to users and applications.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] Some early incarnations of object storage were used for archiving, as implementations were optimized for data services like immutability, not performance.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] EMC Centera and Hitachi HCP (formerly known as HCAP) are two commonly cited object storage products for archiving.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] Another example is Quantum ActiveScale Object Storage Platform.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] More general-purpose object-storage systems came to market around 2008.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] A few object-storage systems support Unified File and Object storage, allowing clients to store objects on a storage system while simultaneously other clients store files on the same storage system.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] Other vendors in the area of Hybrid cloud storage are using Cloud storage gateways to provide a file access layer over object storage, implementing file access protocols such as SMB and NFS.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] Some large Internet companies developed their own software when object-storage products were not commercially available or use cases were very specific.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] Facebook famously invented their own object-storage software, code-named Haystack, to address their particular massive-scale photo management needs efficiently.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] Object storage at the protocol and device layer was proposed 20 years ago and approved for the SCSI command set nearly 10 years ago as "Object-based Storage Device Commands" (OSD), however, it had not been put into production until the development of the Seagate Kinetic Open Storage platform.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] The SCSI command set for Object Storage Devices was developed by a working group of the SNIA for the T10 committee of the International Committee for Information Technology Standards (INCITS).
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] T10 is responsible for all SCSI standards.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] One of the first object-storage products, Lustre, is used in 70% of the Top 100 supercomputers and ~50% of the Top 500.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] As of June 16, 2013, this includes 7 of the top 10, including the current fourth fastest system on the list - China's Tianhe-2 and the seventh fastest, the Titan supercomputer at the Oak Ridge National Laboratory.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] Object-storage systems had good adoption in the early 2000s as an archive platform, particularly in the wake of compliance laws like Sarbanes-Oxley.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] After five years in the market, EMC's Centera product claimed over 3,500 customers and 150 petabytes shipped by 2007.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] Hitachi's HCP product also claims many petabyte-scale customers.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] Newer object storage systems have also gotten some traction, particularly around very large custom applications like eBay's auction site, where EMC Atmos is used to manage over 500 million objects a day.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] As of March 3, 2014, EMC claims to have sold over 1.5 exabytes of Atmos storage.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] On July 1, 2014, Los Alamos National Lab chose the Scality RING as the basis for a 500-petabyte storage environment, which would be among the largest ever.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] "Captive" object storage systems like Facebook's Haystack have scaled impressively.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] In April 2009, Haystack was managing 60 billion photos and 1.5 petabytes of storage, adding 220 million photos and 25 terabytes a week.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] Facebook more recently stated that they were adding 350 million photos a day and were storing 240 billion photos.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] This could equal as much as 357 petabytes.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] Cloud storage has become pervasive as many new web and mobile applications choose it as a common way to store binary data.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] As the storage back-end to many popular applications like Smugmug and Dropbox, Amazon S3 has grown to massive scale, citing over 2-trillion objects stored in April 2013.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] Two months later, Microsoft claimed that they stored even more objects in Azure at 8.5 trillion.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] By April 2014, Azure claimed over 20-trillion objects stored.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] Windows Azure Storage manages Blobs (user files), Tables (structured storage), and Queues (message delivery) and counts them all as objects.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] Coldago Research adopted qualitative and quantitative analysis of the object storage market to rank 13 notable vendors based on technological capabilities, market momentum, and innovation trajectory.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] The 2024 Coldago object storage market leader rating is in alphabetical order: Cloudian, DataCore, Dell EMC, Huawei, IBM, MinIO, Pure Storage, Quantum, and VAST Data.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] In the first version of the OSD standard, objects are specified with a 64-bit partition ID and a 64-bit object ID.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] Partitions are created and deleted within an OSD, and objects are created and deleted within partitions.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] There are no fixed sizes associated with partitions or objects; they are allowed to grow subject to physical size limitations of the device or logical quota constraints on a partition.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] An extensible set of attributes describe objects.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] Some attributes are implemented directly by the OSD, such as the number of bytes in an object and the modification time of an object.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] There is a special policy tag attribute that is part of the security mechanism.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] Other attributes are uninterpreted by the OSD.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] These are set on objects by the higher-level storage systems that use the OSD for persistent storage.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] For example, attributes might be used to classify objects, or to capture relationships among different objects stored on different OSDs.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] A list command returns a list of identifiers for objects within a partition, optionally filtered by matches against their attribute values.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] A list command can also return selected attributes of the listed objects.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] Read and write commands can be combined, or piggy-backed, with commands to get and set attributes.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] This ability reduces the number of times a high-level storage system has to cross the interface to the OSD, which can improve overall efficiency.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] A second generation of the SCSI command set, "Object-Based Storage Devices - 2" (OSD-2) added support for snapshots, collections of objects, and improved error handling.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] A snapshot is a point-in-time copy of all the objects in a partition into a new partition.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] The OSD can implement a space-efficient copy using copy-on-write techniques so that the two partitions share objects that are unchanged between the snapshots, or the OSD might physically copy the data to the new partition.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] The standard defines clones, which are writeable, and snapshots, which are read-only.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] A collection is a special kind of object that contains the identifiers of other objects.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] There are operations to add and delete from collections, and there are operations to get or set attributes for all the objects in a collection.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] Collections are also used for error reporting.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] If an object becomes damaged by the occurrence of a media defect (i.e., a bad spot on the disk) or by a software error within the OSD implementation, its identifier is put into a special error collection.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] The higher-level storage system that uses the OSD can query this collection and take corrective action as necessary.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] The border between an object store and a key–value store is blurred, with key–value stores being sometimes loosely referred to as object stores.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] A traditional block storage interface uses a series of fixed size blocks which are numbered starting at 0.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] Data must be that exact fixed size and can be stored in a particular block which is identified by its logical block number (LBN).
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] Later, one can retrieve that block of data by specifying its unique LBN.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] With a key–value store, data is identified by a key rather than a LBN.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] A key might be "cat" or "olive" or "42".
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] It can be an arbitrary sequence of bytes of arbitrary length.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] Data (called a value in this parlance) does not need to be a fixed size and also can be an arbitrary sequence of bytes of arbitrary length.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] One stores data by presenting the key and data (value) to the data store and can later retrieve the data by presenting the key.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] This concept is seen in programming languages.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] Python calls them dictionaries, Perl calls them hashes, Java, Rust and C++ call them maps, etc.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] Several data stores also implement key–value stores such as Memcached, Redis and CouchDB.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] Object stores are similar to key–value stores in two respects.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] First, the object identifier or URL (the equivalent of the key) can be an arbitrary string.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] Second, data may be of an arbitrary size.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] There are, however, a few key differences between key–value stores and object stores.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] First, object stores also allow one to associate a limited set of attributes (metadata) with each piece of data.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] The combination of a key, value, and set of attributes is referred to as an object.
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] Second, object stores are optimized for large amounts of data (hundreds of megabytes or even gigabytes), whereas for key–value stores the value is expected to be relatively small (kilobytes).
[src:aws-s3/object-storage] Finally, object stores usually offer weaker consistency guarantees such as eventual consistency, whereas key–value stores offer strong consistency.
